    <string name="search_instructions_notes">
        If the input search text is less than three (3) characters and a number, the Search API will only return matching “line” objects.\n\n
        Non-numeric search terms less than three (3) characters will not return any results.
        The Search API includes a suburb search.\n\n

        If the search term is also the name of (or part of the name of) a suburb, Search will return the following:\n
        \n\t\t stops with the search term in the location name
        \n\t\t stops with the search term in the suburb field
        \n\t\t lines that travel through suburbs that contain the search term (though these suburbs are not visible as they are not returned as part of the “line” object)\n\n
        For example, searching for “fitzroy” returns\n

        \n\t\t stops with “fitzroy” in the suburb field (e.g. suburb: “Fitzroy North”)
        \n\t\t stops with “fitzroy” in the location_name field (e.g. “Acland St/Fitzroy St #135”)
        \n\t\t lines that travel through suburbs that contain “fitzroy”\n\n

        You can filter search results by transport mode by using the name of the mode as part of your search. For example:\n
        \n\t\t “tram carnegie” returns tram stops and lines relevant to Carnegie
        \n\t\t “tram 3” returns tram lines that contain the number “3”
        \n\t\t “whitehorse bus” returns bus lines and stops containing the word “whitehorse”\n\n

        You can also filter by suburb, for example:\n\n

        \t\t “william, fitzroy” returns stops with “william” in the location_name and in suburbs Fitzroy or Fitzroy North
        \n\t\t (The input order for these combinations does not matter – e.g. “tram 3” and “3 tram” return the same results.)\n\n

        You can also use the word “route” with numeric search terms to limit results to “line” objects, for example:\n\n

        \t\t “route 900” returns the Route 900 line
    </string>

